## IntentSig Commit Format

When writing commit messages, prefer the structured format:

```
[INTENT] What this transformation achieves
[SCOPE] Files or areas affected
[CRITERIA] How to verify success
```

This gives higher V (Vector alignment) in the Gamma computation. Plain messages are accepted (minimum 10 characters) but produce lower coherence scores.

## Causal Handshake Merge Format

When writing merge messages, use:

```
[SYN] What this merge achieves
[DATA] What changed / evidence
[SEAL] How it was verified
[FIN] Result
```

SYN + DATA required. SEAL + FIN raise merge coherence.

## Symbol Rendering

- In Unicode contexts (markdown, corpus, display): use ΔGENCY, ΔEON, ΔCME
- In ASCII/code contexts (filenames, variables, CLI): use DGENCY, DEON, DCME
- Both forms are canonical. Context determines rendering.

## Anti-Circularity Constraint

No system may validate its own transformations. This is enforced at every level:
- Git hooks run locally but cannot be bypassed on push (pre-push validates DAG)
- GitHub Actions runs on Microsoft infrastructure (Design Ledger has no control)
- Branch protection requires review from a different author
- The validator (github.com) is never the validated (thedesignledger/son-console)

When writing code, never create patterns where an entity validates itself.

